Milestone 1: Discovery & Requirements
Discovery
The project began with broad discovery across the fitness and nutrition industry. Interviews and informal discussions were conducted with approximately 28 fitness-related businesses to identify common operational challenges. While several pain points emerged, nutrition planning consistently stood out as one of the most time-consuming and inefficient processes. Based on alignment, accessibility, and real-world applicability, the team decided to focus specifically on Peak Fitness as the primary stakeholder for this project.

 

Pain Points
Through stakeholder interviews, several key pain points were identified. Coaches were spending excessive time manually building meal plans, often relying on spreadsheets and inconsistent nutrition data sources. Scaling client load created bottlenecks, reduced plan quality, and increased burnout. Additionally, existing nutrition software solutions were either too limited in functionality or prohibitively expensive for small businesses.


Requirements
To address these pain points, the system needed to automate meal plan generation while maintaining accuracy, affordability, and coach oversight. Core requirements included consistent nutrition data, support for dietary restrictions and preferences, scalable automation, and the ability for coaches to review and approve plans before delivery. These requirements guided all subsequent design and development decisions.


Milestone 2: N8N Infrastructure & Data Model
System Architecture
During this phase, the overall system architecture was designed. The team selected n8n as the automation platform due to its flexibility, transparency, and suitability for rule-based logic. Data flow was structured to separate intake processing, calculation logic, food selection, and output delivery, ensuring maintainability and scalability.

Flow A: Nutrition Plan Generator
 

Flow B: Manual Food Uploader (custom food bank)
 

Custom Food Database
A major focus of this milestone was the creation of a custom food database. Existing nutrition databases were found to be inconsistent and unreliable for automation. Hundreds of food entries were manually curated, normalized to a standard serving size, and tagged with macro values, micronutrients, dietary indicators, food categories, and meal classifications. This ensured deterministic and accurate automation results.

Data Normalization
All nutrition data was standardized to consistent units and formats to eliminate discrepancies between sources. This normalization step was critical to ensuring that calculations, comparisons, and filtering logic behaved predictably within automated workflows.

Milestone 3: Intake Workflow & Rules Engine
Intake Workflow
A structured digital intake workflow was developed to collect client information, including goals, dietary preferences, restrictions, and health considerations. Validation logic ensured that required fields were present before automation execution began.

Rules Engine
Nutrition logic was translated into a rule-based engine capable of calculating calorie and macronutrient targets. Food selection rules were applied to filter items based on dietary constraints, preferences, and macro compatibility. The rules engine ensured consistent behavior across all client profiles.

Error Handling & Edge Cases
Conditional logic and fallback paths were implemented to handle restrictive diets, missing data, or conflicting inputs. This prevented system failures and ensured reliable plan generation under a wide range of scenarios.





















Milestone 4: Trainer Dashboard & Delivery
Trainer Review Workflow
A coach-facing review step was implemented to allow trainers to inspect and adjust generated meal plans before delivery. This preserved professional oversight while still benefiting from automation efficiency.


 




















User Interface Requirements
Functional UI requirements were defined to ensure the system aligned with real coaching workflows. Interfaces were designed to be intuitive, modern, and efficient, minimizing friction for trainers.


 



















Plan Delivery
Finalized meal plans were structured for clear presentation and easy delivery to clients. This milestone ensured that automation outputs were not only accurate but also usable in a real business setting.

 





Milestone 5: Security, Testing & Final Demo
Testing & Validation
Automated workflows were tested across multiple client scenarios to validate calculation accuracy, rule enforcement, and system stability. Outputs were compared against manually created plans to confirm correctness.

Security & Reliability
Basic security considerations were addressed, including controlled data access and structured data handling. Workflow resilience was improved through defensive logic and validation checks.

Image of secure coach log in screen
 

Final Demonstration
The final milestone concluded with documentation finalization and the creation of a professional marketing-style demonstration video. This demo showcased the platform’s functionality, value proposition, and future expansion potential.








